-- SE Asia Stocks -Indonesia posts best gain since April; Malaysia at all-time high 
-- By Kaweewit Keawjinga and Viparat Jantraprap
-- Mon Jul 07, 2014 07:12AM EDT
-- None



BANGKOK, July 7 (Reuters) - Indonesian shares posted their best gain in three months on Monday amid a rise in the rupiah <IDR=ID> and inflows into large-caps while the Malaysian benchmark hit an all-time closing high, with banking shares leading the pack.

Foreign investors cautiously built positions in equities again, with the presidential election just two days away. They were net buyers of big-caps such as Telkom Indonesia <TLKM.JK> and Bank Rakyat Indonesia <BBRI.JK>, Thomson Reuters data showed. [ID:nL4N0P62OK] The Indonesian stock market recorded its first net foreign buying in three days, bringing in a net 760.6 billion rupiah ($65.04 million). It saw a fall in inflows to $234 million in May, a third of the month earlier, amid election uncertainty <.VMFIN.JK>. Jakarta's composite index <.JKSE> closed up 1.7 percent, recording its biggest gain since April 1, while the rupiah extended gains to a five-week high. [ID:nL4N0PI1TE] Kuala Lumpur's composite index <.KLSE> rose 0.4 percent to a record close of 1,892.50, amid active buying in shares of Maybank <MBBM.KL> and Public Bank <PUBM.KL>, with interest rates seen on the rise. Malaysia's central bank is expected to raise its key interest rate to 3.25 percent at a policy meeting on Thursday, a Reuters poll showed. [ID:nB9N0ND00Y] The Philippines <.PSI> recorded inflows worth a net 901 million pesos ($20.72 million) with foreign buying in shares such as Bank of the Philippine Islands <BPI.PS> and property shares including Megaworld <MEG.PS>. In Bangkok, the SET index <.SETI> closed above a psychological level of 1,500, helped by a 2.2 percent jump in shares of top energy firm PTT <PTT.BK> and foreign inflows worth a net 1.7 billion baht ($30.86 million). <TH/TRADING02> Singapore posted a fifth straight gain while Vietnam <.VNI> ended near a three-month high. [ID:nL4N0PI231]